    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nThis line of code is passing UINT32_MAX (`_Py_IMMORTAL_REFCNT_LOCAL`) to a function that takes a `Py_ssize_t` as an argument. On 32 bit systems, this overflows to -1, leading to crashes.\n\nhttps://github.com/cython/cython/blob/2d06b4992eeafbf52171a24b79df761a09727385/Cython/Compiler/Code.py#L2529\n\nNumPy hit this trying to build win32 wheels for our nightly CI: https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/31607\n\nOne fix is to use the code path in `Py_SET_REFCNT` for overflowing arguments:\n\nhttps://github.com/python/cpython/blob/f4f102027a9b0edc72a048f17b696aa92d2e6893/Include/refcount.h#L177-L182\n\nThis code already only fires on the free-threaded build, so I think it's safe to substitute the code that manually sets PyObject internals.\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\nThis happens for all Cython modules on 32bit architectures using the free-threaded build. It triggers an assert in CPython on 3.15t:\n\n```\nAssertion failed: refcnt >= 0, file C:\\Users\\goldbaum\\AppData\\Local\\Python\\pythoncore-3.15t-32\\Include\\refcount.g, line 155\nFatal Python error: Aborted\n```\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\nNo asserts when I import Cython modules.\n\n### OS\n\nWindows\n\n### Python version\n\n3.15t 32 bit\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.2.5\n\n### Additional context\n\nI used Claude to identify the bug and for the suggested fix.\n\nI'm going to work around this in the NumPy CI by disabling constant immortalization for the NumPy cython tests, with a TODO to revert that once this issue is fixed in Cython in a released version.",
